les over patents, production, exhibition, and the reception of film, readers learn how going to the movies became a social tradition in American society. In the course of these two decades, cinema succeeded both in establishing itself among other entertainment and instructional media and in updating various forms of spectacle.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxPlots, themes, etc. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh1 aGaudreault, Andre, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813546445423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813546445.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK